old almost no brands made it through unscathed.=C2=A0

The Confidence Game
-------------------

Many E.L.C. employees have described de La Faverie, who has been at Lauder =
since 2011,
as someone =E2=80=9Cgenuinely willing to try something different,=E2=80=9D =
with a leadership style that=E2=80=99s a =E2=80=9Cbreath of fresh air.=E2=
=80=9D But there=E2=80=99s also a prevailing notion that there hasn=E2=80=
=99t been enough change at the highest levels. =E2=80=9CIf E.L.C. really wa=
nted to shake it up, they would have cleaned house at the top,=E2=80=9D the=
 executive said.

=C2=A0

Sure, but to an extent, the company has done just that. Over the past year,=
 there
has been considerable reshuffling at the top: Fabrizio Freda, Tracey Travis=
, Deirdre Stanley, and Jane Lauder=E2=80=93=E2=80=93former C.E.O., C.F.O., =
general counsel, and chief data officer, respectively=E2=80=93=E2=80=93have=
 all departed, as well as the heads of North America, International, and Tr=
avel Retail, who have all left or announced they would be exiting. I=E2=80=
=99m also hearing it was announced internally that E.V.P. of Online Gibu
Thomas will be leaving his role effective April 1. Even H.R. is getting a m=
illennial makeover, following the announcement that longtime human resource=
s head Michael O=E2=80=99Hare is retiring, to be replaced by Michael Bowes,=
 who will have a new, slightly warmer-sounding title: chief people officer.=
=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Another former executive told me that they would=E2=80=99ve had more
confidence in E.L.C.=E2=80=99s future if the new leadership team had more o=
f a 50-50 split between internal promotions and external hires. =E2=80=9CTo=
 say that everyone in a position of leadership needs to come from the outsi=
de is not realistic, because it=E2=80=99s a huge organization to have to tr=
averse,=E2=80=9D this person said. They added that =E2=80=9Cto keep all of =
the same people in essentially the same roles signals that nothing has real=
ly changed.=E2=80=9D I tend to agree.

=C2=A0

So what, if anything, do the leadership changes say about the future of the=
 company=E2=80=94and which brands they may soon offload? Well, probably not=
 as much as the layoffs do. As for divestitures, it=E2=80=99s Lauder=E2=80=
=99s haircare =E2=80=9Ccluster=E2=80=9D (Aveda, Bumble and Bumble) that act=
ually has a chance to excel in the hands of different owners, at least acco=
rding to the executive I spoke to. =E2=80=9CGrowth in beauty is happening i=
n fragrance and hair=E2=80=A6 period,=E2=80=9D this person said. =E2=80=9CA=
nd the
challenge is that we don=E2=80=99t know the salon network. We don=E2=80=99t=
 know how to optimize the salon channel and West Coast brands.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Another high-level source told me that Henkel, which counts GOT2B, Schwarzk=
opf, and Joico among its haircare brands, was at one time looking at Bumble=
 and Bumble and Aveda. I think this would be a good fit=E2=80=94as would Ye=
llow Wood Partners, which in 2023 completed its acquisition of Suave, anoth=
er haircare
brand, albeit mass priced. A person with knowledge of the matter told me th=
at Lauder=E2=80=99s haircare brands are not for sale at this time. =E2=80=
=9CThe goal is to put them in the right spots and to turn them around,=E2=
=80=9D this person said. Really, the only place for Smashbox and Glamglow t=
o go is private equity, but I=E2=80=99m not sure why Lauder doesn=E2=80=99t=
 just shutter them altogether, like it did with Becca Cosmetics a few years=
 ago.=C2=A0

=E2=80=8A

