ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">When I first heard about the <em>clusters </em>idea, I thought it was a=
 welcome
development. Est=C3=A9e Lauder should be organizing brands by category rath=
er than allowing favored executives to gerrymander their portfolios by pick=
ing their favorite brands. But I quickly realized most of the changes were =
merely, alas, cosmetic<em>.</em> Aside from newly formed clusters in skinca=
re (La Mer, Clinique, Origins, Dr.Jart+, Darphin, and Lab Series) and makeu=
p (MAC Cosmetics, Bobbi Brown, Too Faced, Smashbox, and Glamglow) that will=
 be overseen by <strong>Sandra Main</strong> and a
=E2=80=9Cto-be-named=E2=80=9D executive, much of the brand leadership is th=
e <em>same</em>.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">To wit: Est=C3=A9e Lauder the brand, a=
s well as Aerin, will continue to operate independently under <strong>Justi=
n Boxford</strong>, who=E2=80=99s been global brand president since 2022. T=
he same goes for =E2=80=9Ccouture brands=E2=80=9D Tom Ford and Balmain, und=
er <strong>Guillaume Jesel</strong>; haircare lines Aveda and Bumble and Bu=
mble, under
<strong>Shane Wolf</strong>; Deciem, parentco of The Ordinary, under <stron=
g>Jesper Rasmussen</strong>; and Le Labo, under <strong>Deborah Royer</stro=
ng>.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>Then there=E2=80=99s <strong>Jane Hudis=
</strong>, the longtime executive group president and de La Faverie=E2=80=
=99s onetime boss, who I previously reported would receive the biggest prom=
otion of all. Indeed, Hudis was just anointed chief brand officer, a newly =
created role. My Instagram was abuzz with
congratulatory praise for Hudis, who has spent more than 30 years at the co=
mpany and will now essentially act as de La Faverie=E2=80=99s number two.=
=C2=A0</p><br/><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">So much of the insi=
der chatter at the company also coalesced around an executive who was
notably <em>absent</em> from the lengthy list of promotions and updates: <s=
trong>Michelle Freyre</strong>, global brand president of Clinique and Orig=
ins, whom a current executive credited with =E2=80=9Ccatapulting Clinique b=
ack to popularity with younger customers.=E2=80=9D Even though Freyre has =
=E2=80=9Ca lot of street cred with employees,=E2=80=9D she won=E2=80=99t be=
 heading up any of the newly formed clusters. I=E2=80=99m told she was a to=
p contender to lead the skincare group, but it=E2=80=99s Main=E2=80=93=E2=
=80=93responsible for La Mer=E2=80=99s explosive growth in
the 2010s=E2=80=93=E2=80=93who ultimately got the job. I=E2=80=99m hoping t=
hat Freyre, who joined Lauder in 2020 after nearly two decades at Johnson &=
amp; Johnson, eventually gets elevated in some way, even if it=E2=80=99s no=
t leading makeup. I did hear Lauder is looking both internally <em>and </em=
>externally for this position, but it seems like no one=E2=80=99s in line t=
o fill the role yet.</p></div>
