x;">Many E.L.C. employees have described de La Faverie, who has been at Lau=
der since 2011,
as someone =E2=80=9Cgenuinely willing to try something different,=E2=80=9D =
with a leadership style that=E2=80=99s a =E2=80=9Cbreath of fresh air.=E2=
=80=9D But there=E2=80=99s also a prevailing notion that there hasn=E2=80=
=99t been <em>enough </em>change at the highest levels. =E2=80=9CIf E.L.C. =
really wanted to shake it up, they would have cleaned house at the top,=E2=
=80=9D the executive said.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Sure, but to an extent, the=
 company has done just that. Over the past year, there
has been <em>considerable</em> reshuffling at the top: <strong>Fabrizio Fre=
da</strong>, <strong>Tracey Travis</strong>, <strong>Deirdre Stanley</stron=
g>, and <strong>Jane Lauder</strong>=E2=80=93=E2=80=93former C.E.O., C.F.O.=
, general counsel, and chief data officer, respectively=E2=80=93=E2=80=93ha=
ve all departed, as well as the heads of North America, International, and =
Travel Retail, who have all left or announced they would be exiting. I=E2=
=80=99m also hearing it was announced internally that E.V.P. of Online <str=
ong>Gibu
Thomas</strong> will be leaving his role effective April 1. Even H.R. is ge=
tting a millennial makeover, following the announcement that longtime human=
 resources head <strong>Michael O=E2=80=99Hare</strong> is retiring, to be =
replaced by <strong>Michael Bowes</strong>, who will have a new, slightly w=
armer-sounding title: chief people officer.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;m=
argin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Anoth=
er former executive told me that they would=E2=80=99ve had more
confidence in E.L.C.=E2=80=99s future if the new leadership team had more o=
f a 50-50 split between internal promotions and external hires. =E2=80=9CTo=
 say that everyone in a position of leadership needs to come from the outsi=
de is not realistic, because it=E2=80=99s a huge organization to have to tr=
averse,=E2=80=9D this person said. They added that =E2=80=9Cto keep all of =
the same people in essentially the same roles signals that nothing has real=
ly changed.=E2=80=9D I tend to agree.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom=
:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">So what, if anyth=
ing, do the leadership changes say about the future of the company=E2=80=94=
and which brands they may soon offload? Well, probably not as much as the l=
ayoffs do. As for divestitures, it=E2=80=99s Lauder=E2=80=99s haircare =E2=
=80=9Ccluster=E2=80=9D (Aveda, Bumble and Bumble) that actually has a chanc=
e to excel in the hands of different owners, at least according to the exec=
utive I spoke to. =E2=80=9CGrowth in beauty is happening in fragrance and h=
air=E2=80=A6 period,=E2=80=9D this person said. =E2=80=9CAnd the
challenge is that we don=E2=80=99t know the salon network. We don=E2=80=99t=
 know how to optimize the salon channel and West Coast brands.=E2=80=9D</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">A=
nother high-level source told me that Henkel, which counts GOT2B, Schwarzko=
pf, and Joico among its haircare brands, was at one time looking at Bumble =
and Bumble and Aveda. I think this would be a good fit=E2=80=94as would Yel=
low Wood Partners, which in 2023 completed its acquisition of Suave, anothe=
r haircare
brand, albeit mass priced. A person with knowledge of the matter told me th=
at Lauder=E2=80=99s haircare brands are not for sale at this time. =E2=80=
=9CThe goal is to put them in the right spots and to turn them around,=E2=
=80=9D this person said. Really, the only place for Smashbox and Glamglow t=
o go is private equity, but I=E2=80=99m not sure why Lauder doesn=E2=80=99t=
 just shutter them altogether, like it did with Becca Cosmetics a few years=
 ago.=C2=A0</p></div>
